Dragon Ball Supervised Learning Classification¶

Problem Definition¶

Can we accurately predict whether a Dragon Ball character will win or lose a fight based on their attributes such as Power Level, Race, Transformations, Techniques, and Previous Battles?

Context¶

  • In the Dragon Ball universe, battles are determined by various factors, including a fighter’s power level, race, transformations, fighting techniques, and experience.
  • Using machine learning classification models, we can estimate the probability of winning based on these attributes.
  • This could be useful for game balancing, AI-driven character matchups, competitive strategy analysis, and fan discussions.

Objective¶

  • Develop a classification model to predict whether a character will win or lose a battle.
  • Identify key features that contribute the most to battle outcomes.
  • Compare the performance of different models (Logistic Regression, Random Forest, XGBoost, and SVM) to determine the best approach.
  • Analyze how race, transformations, and fighting styles impact battle success.

Data Dictionary¶

  • Name: Character's name
  • Race: The species of the fighter (Saiyan, Namekian, etc.)
  • Gender: Male or Female
  • Power Level: The numeric power level (Target Variable)
  • Y Variable (Target)
  • Ki Blast: Character’s energy attack technique
  • Melee Combat: Fighting style and close-combat abilities
  • Speed: Speed level (Numeric)
  • Special Attack: Ultimate moves or techniques
  • Transformation: The highest transformation level achieved (Super Saiyan, etc.)
  • Speed_Original: Descriptive speed category (Fast, Medium, Slow)
  • Normalized_Power: Scaled power level (0-1)
  • Power_Score: Normalized score based on battle metrics
  • Meta: Combined metadata of character attributes

    • The distribution of Ki Blasts and Melee Combat styles across power levels could indicate which techniques are most associated with high-powered characters.

    • Each special attack is linked to only a single instance in the dataset, suggesting that special attacks alone might not be a reliable indicator of power level.

  • Data Sparsity and Feature Engineering:
    • Since many special attacks are unique to a single character, they might not be helpful in predictive modeling unless grouped into broader categories (e.g., energy-based vs. physical-based).
    • Techniques with higher occurrences might be stronger predictors than those appearing only once.

EDA Analysis¶

  • Categorical and Numerical Variables:
    • The dataset primarily consists of categorical variables such as Race, Ki - Blast, Melee Combat, Special Attack, and Transformation.
    • The only numerical variable is Speed, as power-related features were removed due to redundancy.
  • Feature Selection:
    • Columns like Name, Meta, Power Level, Gender, Normalized Power, Power Score, and Speed_Original were dropped since they were either identifiers, redundant, or derived features.
    • The remaining categorical features were grouped to be encoded appropriately for the classification model.
  • Cross-tabulations & Distributions:
    • Race vs Power Level: Certain races tend to have higher power levels, indicating a potential strong correlation.
    • Transformation vs Power Level: Characters with transformations generally have higher power levels, confirming that transformations impact battle performance.
    • Special Attacks & Techniques: The dataset shows a high number of unique special attacks, making them difficult to use directly as features. Grouping into broader categories (e.g., energy-based vs. physical-based) could improve model effectiveness.
  • Data Sparsity & Feature Engineering:
    • Many special attacks appeared only once in the dataset, making them unreliable as individual predictive features.
    • Aggregating them into broader classifications (e.g., ki-based vs. melee-based attacks) may enhance predictive power.
  • Potential Challenges:
    • Class Imbalance: If some races or transformations appear significantly more than others, the model might be biased towards them.
    • High Dimensionality: Encoding categorical variables may introduce a large number of features, requiring dimensionality reduction techniques like PCA or feature selection.

Define Transformation Levels

In [21]:
# Define ordinal encoding for transformations
transformation_levels = {
    '-': 0,  # No transformation
    'Super Saiyan': 1,
    'Super Saiyan 2': 2,
    'Final Form': 3,
    'Perfect Form': 4,
    'Majin Form': 4,  # Equivalent to Perfect Form in strength
    'Absorption': 5,
    'Merge with Piccolo': 6,
    'Fuse with Kami': 7,
    'Various Forms': 8  # Miscellaneous transformations
}

Create Win/Loss Column¶

Generate All Possible Matchups

In [29]:
from itertools import combinations

# Generate all possible matchups
battle_pairs = list(combinations(data.index, 2))

# Create a DataFrame for battles
battle_df = pd.DataFrame(battle_pairs, columns=['Character_1', 'Character_2'])

# Merge attributes from the original dataset for both characters
battle_df = battle_df.merge(data, left_on='Character_1', right_index=True, suffixes=('_1', ''))
battle_df = battle_df.merge(data, left_on='Character_2', right_index=True, suffixes=('_1', '_2'))

# Assign winner based on power level, speed, and transformation level
battle_df['Winner'] = np.where(
    (battle_df['Power Level_1'] > battle_df['Power Level_2']) |
    ((battle_df['Power Level_1'] == battle_df['Power Level_2']) & (battle_df['Speed_1'] > battle_df['Speed_2'])) |
    ((battle_df['Power Level_1'] == battle_df['Power Level_2']) &
     (battle_df['Speed_1'] == battle_df['Speed_2']) &
     (battle_df['Transformation_Level_1'] > battle_df['Transformation_Level_2'])),
    battle_df['Character_1'],  # Character_1 wins
    battle_df['Character_2']   # Character_2 wins
)

Calculate Each Character's Win Rate

In [30]:
# Count wins for each character
win_counts = battle_df['Winner'].value_counts().reset_index()
win_counts.columns = ['Character', 'Wins']

# Count total battles for each character
total_battles = pd.concat([battle_df['Character_1'], battle_df['Character_2']]).value_counts().reset_index()
total_battles.columns = ['Character', 'Total_Battles']

# Merge win counts with total battles
win_loss_stats = total_battles.merge(win_counts, on='Character', how='left').fillna(0)

# Compute win rate
win_loss_stats['Win_Rate'] = win_loss_stats['Wins'] / win_loss_stats['Total_Battles']
win_loss_stats.drop(columns=['Wins'], inplace=True)

# Convert win rate into a binary target: 1 if win rate > 0.5, else 0
win_loss_stats['Win_Loss_Label'] = (win_loss_stats['Win_Rate'] > 0.5).astype(int)
  • Character_1_Wins = 1 → Character_1 won
  • Character_1_Wins = 0 → Character_2 won

Merge Datasets

In [31]:
# Merge win/loss stats into original dataset
data = data.merge(win_loss_stats[['Character', 'Win_Loss_Label']], left_index=True, right_on='Character', how='left')

# Drop redundant 'Character' column after merging (if necessary)
data.drop(columns=['Character'], inplace=True)

Scaling Options

from sklearn.preprocessing import (
    StandardScaler, MinMaxScaler, RobustScaler, MaxAbsScaler,
    PowerTransformer, QuantileTransformer, Normalizer
)

# 📌 Load dataset (Modify path if needed)
#file_path = "your_dataset.csv"  # Update with correct file
#data = pd.read_csv(file_path)

# 📌 Select numeric columns only
numeric_features = data.select_dtypes(include=['number']).dropna()

# 📌 Detect Outliers using IQR (Interquartile Range)
def detect_outliers(df):
    outlier_info = {}
    for column in df.columns:
        Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

        # Count outliers
        outlier_count = ((df[column] < lower_bound) | (df[column] > upper_bound)).sum()
        outlier_info[column] = outlier_count

    return outlier_info

outliers = detect_outliers(numeric_features)
outlier_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(outliers, orient='index', columns=['Outlier Count'])

# 📌 Check Skewness (to determine if transformation is needed)
skewness = numeric_features.skew()

# 📌 Scaling Options with All Variants
scalers = {
    "StandardScaler": StandardScaler(),
    "MinMaxScaler": MinMaxScaler(),
    "RobustScaler": RobustScaler(),
    "MaxAbsScaler": MaxAbsScaler(),
    "PowerTransformer (Yeo-Johnson)": PowerTransformer(method="yeo-johnson"),
    "PowerTransformer (Box-Cox)": PowerTransformer(method="box-cox"),
    "QuantileTransformer (Normal)": QuantileTransformer(output_distribution="normal"),
    "QuantileTransformer (Uniform)": QuantileTransformer(output_distribution="uniform"),
    "Normalizer (L1)": Normalizer(norm="l1"),
    "Normalizer (L2)": Normalizer(norm="l2"),
    "Normalizer (Max)": Normalizer(norm="max"),
}

scaler_results = {}

# 📌 Try all scalers & transformations
for scaler_name, scaler in scalers.items():
    try:
        transformed_data = scaler.fit_transform(numeric_features)
        transformed_df = pd.DataFrame(transformed_data, columns=numeric_features.columns, index=numeric_features.index)

        # Calculate variance after scaling (Higher is better)
        cumulative_variance = transformed_df.var().sum()
        scaler_results[scaler_name] = cumulative_variance

    except Exception as e:
        print(f"❌ Error with {scaler_name}: {e}")

# 📌 Convert results to DataFrame and Rank
scaler_rank_df = pd.DataFrame(list(scaler_results.items()), columns=['Scaler', 'Cumulative Variance'])
scaler_rank_df = scaler_rank_df.sort_values(by="Cumulative Variance", ascending=False)

# 📌 Pick the best scaler based on variance ranking
best_scaler_name = scaler_rank_df.iloc[0]["Scaler"]
best_scaler = scalers[best_scaler_name]
scaled_data = best_scaler.fit_transform(numeric_features)

# 📌 Convert Scaled Data to DataFrame
scaled_df = pd.DataFrame(scaled_data, columns=numeric_features.columns, index=numeric_features.index)

# 📌 Save the scaled dataset
scaled_df.to_csv("scaled_dataset.csv", index=False)

# 📌 Explain Selection
explanations = {
    "MinMaxScaler": "Scales data between [0,1]. Used in Unsupervised Learning & Deep Learning but NOT recommended for outliers.",
    "StandardScaler": "Standardizes data to mean=0, variance=1. Recommended for Unsupervised Learning & Deep Learning. Works well with outliers.",
    "RobustScaler": "Uses median and IQR. Best choice for handling outliers in both Unsupervised and Supervised Learning.",
    "MaxAbsScaler": "Scales data between [-1,1]. Used for sparse data, not generally needed for typical datasets.",
    "PowerTransformer (Yeo-Johnson)": "Transforms data to be more Gaussian-like. Good for skewed data in Regression & Classification.",
    "PowerTransformer (Box-Cox)": "Similar to Yeo-Johnson but works only with strictly positive values. Reduces skewness.",
    "QuantileTransformer (Normal)": "Maps data to a normal distribution. Works well when distribution is unknown.",
    "QuantileTransformer (Uniform)": "Maps data to a uniform distribution. Useful for highly irregular distributions.",
    "Normalizer (L1)": "Normalizes each row by L1 norm. Good for text-based or sparse datasets.",
    "Normalizer (L2)": "Normalizes each row by L2 norm. Often used in clustering tasks.",
    "Normalizer (Max)": "Normalizes each row by its maximum absolute value. Good for text and sparse data."
}

Model evaluation criterion¶

The Model Can Make Two Types of Wrong Predictions:

  • False Positive (FP): Predicting that a character will win when they actually lose.
  • False Negative (FN): Predicting that a character will lose when they actually win.

Which Case is More Important?

  • The more critical error is False Negative (FN) because:
    • If the model predicts that a character will lose, but they actually win, it fails to identify strong characters correctly.
    • This is a major issue in battle prediction because missing a strong character could lead to incorrect tournament brackets or rankings.
    • FN means underestimating a fighter's strength, which can negatively affect predictions in battles.

How to Reduce False Negatives?

  • The goal is to maximize Recall, ensuring that the model correctly identifies as many winning characters as possible.
  • Higher recall means fewer missed wins (False Negatives), leading to better predictions of strong contenders.
  • If Recall is high, the model is less likely to underestimate powerful characters.

Key Metric: Recall (Sensitivity / True Positive Rate)

  • Use Cases:
    • Important when missing a winning character is more critical.
    • Ensures that strong characters are correctly classified as winners.
    • Useful when identifying battle outcomes where underestimating a fighter’s strength could lead to poor predictions.

Create a function to calculate and print the classification report and the confusion matrix so that we don't have to rewrite the same code repeatedly for each model.

In [49]:
def metrics_score(actual, predicted):
    print(classification_report(actual, predicted))

    # Confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)

    # Plot confusion matrix
    plt.figure(figsize=(7, 4))
    # sns.heatmap(cm, annot = True, fmt = '.2f', xticklabels = ['Not Attrite', 'Attrite'], yticklabels = ['Not Attrite', 'Attrite'])
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt=".2f", xticklabels=["Loss", "Win"], yticklabels=["Loss", "Win"])

    plt.ylabel("Actual")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted")

    plt.show()

Model Evaluation:

  • False Positive (FP): Predicting a character will win when they actually lose.
  • False Negative (FN): Predicting a character will lose when they actually win.

For our Character Battle Outcome Prediction, False Negatives (FN) are more critical because:

  • FN means a strong character is mistakenly classified as a weak one.
  • This leads to underestimating contenders, affecting tournament rankings.
  • Missing a winning character can disrupt predictions for battle matchups.

Chosen Metric: Recall (Sensitivity / True Positive Rate)

  • Recall is the percentage of actual wins (True Positives) correctly classified by the model.
  • Formula:
    [ Recall = \frac{TP}{TP + FN} ]
  • Higher Recall ensures fewer False Negatives, meaning strong contenders are correctly identified.

The Precision-Recall Curve for Logistic Regression

  • It is a useful measure of the success of prediction when the classes are imbalanced.
  • It shows the tradeoff between the precision and the recall for different thresholds.
  • It can be used to select an optimal threshold as required to improve the model performance.
  • If we want a higher precision, we can increase the threshold.
  • If we want a higher recall, we can decrease the threshold.
In [55]:
from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve

# predict_proba gives the probability of each observation belonging to each class
y_scores_lg = lg.predict_proba(x_train)

# Precision and Recall curve

# Plot values of precisions, recalls, and thresholds
plt.figure(figsize = (8, 5))

plt.plot(thresholds_lg, precisions_lg[:-1], 'b--', label = 'precision')
plt.plot(thresholds_lg, recalls_lg[:-1], 'g--', label = 'recall')

plt.xlabel('Threshold')
plt.legend(loc = 'upper left')
plt.ylim([0, 1])

plt.show()
In [56]:
from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve

# Predict probabilities for the positive class (1)
y_scores_lg = lg.predict_proba(x_train)[:, 1]

# Compute Precision-Recall curve
precisions_lg, recalls_lg, thresholds_lg = precision_recall_curve(y_train, y_scores_lg)

# Add a starting threshold of 0 for a smoother curve
thresholds_lg = np.append(thresholds_lg, 1)  # Ensures proper length

# Plot Precision-Recall vs Thresholds
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

plt.plot(thresholds_lg, precisions_lg, 'b--', label='Precision', linewidth=2, marker='o')
plt.plot(thresholds_lg, recalls_lg, 'g-.', label='Recall', linewidth=2, marker='s')

# Formatting
plt.xlabel('Threshold', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Score', fontsize=12)
plt.title('Precision-Recall Curve with Thresholds', fontsize=14)
plt.legend(loc='lower left', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)
plt.ylim([0, 1.05])

# Show the plot
plt.show()
  • Choosing different thresholds can completely change the model's performance. We are looking for "sweet spot" (where they cross).

  • Observations

    • Precision and Recall Trade-off:
      • As the threshold increases, precision increases, meaning that the model is making fewer false positive predictions.
      • recall decreases, meaning that the model is missing more actual positives (False Negatives increase).
    • Threshold Effect:
      • At a lower threshold (~0.2-0.4), recall is relatively high, but precision is lower.
      • At a moderate threshold (~0.6), both precision and recall are well-balanced.
      • At a high threshold (~0.8-1.0), precision is very high, but recall drops significantly, meaning the model is too selective and missing many actual positive cases.

  • If recall is too low, we risk underestimating strong characters, leading to incorrect battle outcomes.

  • If precision is too low, the model might overestimate weaker characters, causing incorrect classifications.

K-Nearest Neighbors (K-NN)¶

KNN Documentation

K-NN uses features from the training data to predict the values of new data points, which means the new data point will be assigned a value based on how similar it is to the data points in the training set.

Note: Scale will need to be changed with KNN because the magnitude at the end will affect the distance/output

The following steps are performed in K-NN:

  • Select K
  • Calculate distance (Euclidean, Manhattan, etc.)
  • Find the K closest neighbors
  • Take majority vote for labels

The “K” in the K-NN algorithm is the number of nearest neighbors we wish to take the vote from. Generally, K is taken to be an odd number when the number of classes is even, so as to get a majority vote. Let's say K=3. In that case, we will make a circle with the new data point as the center just as big as enclosing only the three nearest data points on the plane.

But before actually building the model, we need to identify the value of K to be used in K-NN. We will perform the following steps for the same.

  • For every value of K (from 1 to 15), split the training set into a new train and validation sets (30 times)
  • Scale the training data and the validation data
  • Take the average of the error on these training and the validation sets for each value of K
  • Plot the average train vs validation error for all Ks Choose the optimal K from the plot where the two errors are comparable
In [59]:
# pip install scikit-learn

# Import necessary libraries
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# %%time
knn = KNeighborsClassifier()

# We select the optimal value of K for which the error rate is the least in the validation data
# Let us loop over a few values of K to determine the optimal value of K

knn_many_split = {}

for k in range(1, 15):
  train_error = []
  test_error = []

  lista = []

  knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors = k)

  for i in range(30): # why 30x, 30 iterations took x 1 min 9sec, try as many (more better but time is factor) we take a good average of the 30x
      # Split the training set into a new train and validation sets; size of datsset also important to decide
      # apply GridSearch to find the correct value
      x_train_new, x_val, y_train_new, y_val = train_test_split(x_train, y_train, test_size = 0.20)

      # Fitting K-NN on the training data
      knn.fit(x_train_new, y_train_new)

      # Calculating error on the training data and the validation data
      train_error.append(1 - knn.score(x_train_new, y_train_new))

      test_error.append(1 - knn.score(x_val, y_val))

  lista.append(sum(train_error)/len(train_error))

  lista.append(sum(test_error)/len(test_error))

  knn_many_split[k] = lista

Observations:

  • Precision on the test set is higher for class 1 (winning characters), ensuring that predicted winners are mostly correct.
  • Recall is lower for class 1 on the test set, meaning the model is missing some actual winners.
  • The model misclassifies 8 winning characters as losses (False Negatives) on the training data, and 2 on the test data, which could be problematic since recall is the key focus for the dataset.

  • The model performs slightly worse than logistic regression in terms of recall but offers a balanced trade-off.

Insights

  • You want to minimize False Negatives (FN), meaning that if a character actually wins, the model should correctly predict them as a winner.
  • A False Negative (FN) (predicting a loss when the character actually wins) is a major issue because strong fighters might be underestimated, leading to poor battle predictions.
  • Higher recall ensures that most actual winners are correctly identified, even if it slightly sacrifices precision.

Using GridSearchCV for Hyperparameter tuning of the model

  • Hyperparameter tuning is tricky in the sense that there is no direct way to - - calculate how a change in the hyperparameter value will reduce the loss of your model, so we usually resort to experimentation.
  • Grid search is a model tuning technique that attempts to compute the optimum values of hyperparameters.
  • It is an exhaustive search that is performed on specific parameter values of a model.
  • The parameters of the estimator/model used to apply these methods are optimized by cross-validated grid-search over a parameter grid.

Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)¶

Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) is generally used to classify patterns between two classes; however, it can be extended to classify multiple patterns. LDA assumes that all classes are linearly separable and according to this, multiple linear discrimination functions representing several hyperplanes in the feature space are created to distinguish between the classes. If there are two classes, then the LDA draws one hyperplane and projects the data onto this hyperplane in such a way as to maximize the separation of the two categories. This hyperplane is created according to two criteria considered simultaneously:

  • Maximizing the distance between the means of two classes.
  • Minimizing the variation between each category.

Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA)¶

  • Quadratic discriminant analysis (QDA) is a probabilistic parametric classification technique that represents an evolution of LDA for nonlinear class separations. QDA, like LDA, is based on the hypothesis that the probability density distributions are multivariate normal but, in this case, the dispersion is not the same for all of the categories.

Feature Importance using SHAP Library¶

  • With the aid of a visualization tool called SHAP, or SHapley Additive exPlanations, a machine learning model's output can be made more understandable. By calculating the contribution of each feature to the prediction, it can be used to explain the prediction by any model. The direction of the relationship (positive or negative) between the predictive variable and the target variable is also indicated by the SHAP values. A technique called SHAP values (SHapley Additive exPlanations), which is based on cooperative game theory, is used to make machine learning models more transparent and understandable.

  • In a machine learning setting, a Shapley value is the contribution of a feature value to the difference between the actual prediction and the mean prediction.

SHAP Barplot

  • We plot the mean absolute value for each feature column as a bar chart if an Explainer with many samples is passed.

  • We determine the mean absolute SHAP values across all observations for each feature. Since we do not want positive and negative numbers to cancel one another out, we take the absolute values. A mean SHAP plot will allow us to visualize the aggregated SHAP values.

  • SHAP value helps us quantify feature's contribution towards a prediction. SHAP value closer to zero means the feature contributes little to the prediction whereas SHAP value away from zero indicates the feature contributes more. So, large positive/negative SHAP values are found in features that significantly affect the model's predictions.

    • A character with high Speed (+0.05 SHAP value) but belonging to a race with lower SHAP values (e.g., Race_Justice Beam, 0.00) may have a neutral or lesser impact on their battle success.
      • 

    

    • 

  • Conclusion:
    

      

    • The SHAP analysis confirms that Power Level, Race_Alien, and Race_Human are key determinants in battle outcomes. If optimizing for better predictions, focusing on these variables will enhance model performance.
      • 

    

    •

Conclusion & Recommendations¶






















Conclusion


    

  • Power Level, Race_Alien, and Transformation_Level contribute the most to increasing the prediction score (~0.70).
    

    • 

  • Red indicates features pushing the prediction higher (towards winning), while blue indicates features reducing it.
    

    • 

  • Race_Human has a slight negative effect on the prediction, meaning it reduces the probability of winning.
    

    • 

  • Speed and Race_Android have a negligible impact on the prediction outcome.
    

    • 

  • The model considers Power Level as the strongest feature influencing a positive prediction.
    

    • 

  • Assumption Mismatch: LDA assumes normally distributed features with equal covariance across classes, while QDA assumes different covariances. If these assumptions do not hold, performance drops.
    

    • 

  • High Model Sensitivity: LDA and QDA are highly sensitive to feature distributions, which likely led to misclassifications.
    

    • 

  • Dataset Characteristics: If the dataset is not well-suited for linear decision boundaries, LDA will struggle. Similarly, QDA may overfit due to its higher flexibility.
    

    • 



Model Performance Overview


    

  • Logistic Regression consistently outperformed other models with near-perfect precision and recall, making it the most effective classifier in this context.
    • 

  • K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) underperformed compared to logistic regression, especially in recall. Even with hyperparameter tuning, it struggled to reach the same level of accuracy.
    • 

  • Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) and Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA) had significantly worse performance, especially with adjusted thresholds, indicating that they may not be suitable for this dataset.
    • 

  • Threshold Adjustments did not improve models significantly, particularly in LDA, where setting a threshold of 1 resulted in zero positive predictions.
    • 



Recommendations


    

  • Primary Model Choice
      

    • Logistic Regression is the best performing model and should be used unless interpretability or non-linearity becomes a concern.
      • 

    • If a non-linear model is necessary, further fine-tuning of K-NN or trying more advanced models (e.g., Random Forest, XGBoost) is recommended.
      • 

    

    • 

  • Feature Analysis
      

    • If interpretability is crucial, analyzing feature coefficients from logistic regression can provide insights into how different variables influence battle outcomes.
      • 

    • SHAP values (as explored in earlier analysis) should be further investigated to confirm the most important predictors.
      • 

    

    • 

  • Handling Class Imbalance
      

    • Since recall was a priority (avoiding false negatives), threshold tuning for logistic regression should be explored further.
      • 

    • Techniques like SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling) or class-weight adjustments could improve models with lower recall.
      • 

    

    • 

  • Alternative Models to Explore
      

    • Random Forest or XGBoost could be viable alternatives to improve performance while maintaining interpretability.
      • 

    • Neural Networks (if deep learning is an option) could provide further improvements if enough data is available.
      • 

    

    •
